The paper deals with computational social choice, which is a subfield of computer science that studies voting systems and their properties. The focus of the paper is on the computational complexity of manipulation, bribery, and campaign management in Bucklin and fallback voting, which are voting systems. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory). Additionally, the paper involves analyzing data and making decisions based on that data, which suggests that it could also belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The paper also involves analyzing algorithms and their efficiency, which suggests that it could belong to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). Finally, the paper involves analyzing the computational complexity of the voting systems, which suggests that it could belong to cs.CC (Computational Complexity).
